      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Weather Abroad: Quick Celsius to Fahrenheit for Travellers</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 21, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>You check the weather at your holiday destination and it says 28°C. Is that hot? Cold? Do you need a jacket? If you grew up with Fahrenheit, Celsius weather forecasts can feel meaningless. Here is a practical guide to interpreting temperatures abroad.</p>

      <h2>Weather Temperature Ranges</h2>
      <p>Rather than memorising exact conversions, learn these ranges:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Below 0°C (32°F):</strong> Freezing — ice, snow, heavy winter gear</li>
        <li><strong>0-10°C (32-50°F):</strong> Cold — winter coat, layers, gloves</li>
        <li><strong>10-15°C (50-59°F):</strong> Cool — jacket or sweater weather</li>
        <li><strong>15-20°C (59-68°F):</strong> Mild — light layers, comfortable</li>
        <li><strong>20-25°C (68-77°F):</strong> Warm — t-shirt weather, pleasant</li>
        <li><strong>25-30°C (77-86°F):</strong> Hot — summer clothing, sunscreen</li>
        <li><strong>30-35°C (86-95°F):</strong> Very hot — seek shade, stay hydrated</li>
        <li><strong>35°C+ (95°F+):</strong> Extreme heat — limit outdoor activity</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Quick Mental Conversion Trick</h2>
      <p>For a rough estimate when you are out and about:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Double the Celsius number</li>
        <li>Add 30</li>
      </ol>
      <p>This gets you within a few degrees:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>10°C: (10 × 2) + 30 = 50°F (actual: 50°F — perfect)</li>
        <li>20°C: (20 × 2) + 30 = 70°F (actual: 68°F — close enough)</li>
        <li>30°C: (30 × 2) + 30 = 90°F (actual: 86°F — close)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>City Weather in Context</h2>
      <p>Popular destinations and their typical summer/winter temperatures:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>London:</strong> Winter 5°C (41°F), Summer 22°C (72°F)</li>
        <li><strong>Paris:</strong> Winter 4°C (39°F), Summer 25°C (77°F)</li>
        <li><strong>Tokyo:</strong> Winter 5°C (41°F), Summer 30°C (86°F)</li>
        <li><strong>Dubai:</strong> Winter 19°C (66°F), Summer 42°C (108°F)</li>
        <li><strong>Sydney:</strong> Winter 13°C (55°F), Summer 26°C (79°F)</li>
        <li><strong>Bangkok:</strong> Year-round 28-35°C (82-95°F)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Packing Tips Based on Temperature</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Below 10°C:</strong> Pack thermal base layers, insulated jacket, scarf, warm socks</li>
        <li><strong>10-20°C:</strong> Layers work best — cardigan plus a light waterproof jacket</li>
        <li><strong>20-30°C:</strong> Light fabrics, shorts, sunglasses, sunscreen, hat</li>
        <li><strong>Above 30°C:</strong> Loose linen or cotton, wide-brimmed hat, water bottle</li>
      </ul>

      <p>When in doubt, check both the daytime high and overnight low at your destination. Many places have a 10-15°C swing between day and night.</p>

